(232,'3EB035C4E5F4533622BA46','642102635659@s.whatsapp.net',NULL,'Dwayne Baird','642102635659@s.whatsapp.net','Dwayne Baird',0,'Ha, that\'ll mean touching the network detection stack, which is genuinely delicate. Right now it handles: detecting the current network, failing over to the internal AP when it drops, ethernet hotplug detection, and suppressing the ghost network that forms during interface checks (the same checks that cause the hostname to shift from forgebox to forgebox-2, in your instance that\'s nix, if the balance is off). I spent a lot of time getting that right, so any changes will poke at that logic.\n\nThe safest path would be to disable ethernet entirely and strip out the AP heartbeat/failover scripts, then add a wifi join option into the SSH menu as a proper infrastructure step. That way you\'re simplifying the stack rather than layering on top of something very complex and designed to make it bulletproof for end users (I need to admit, it\'s bulletproof on the outside, but one small change to it\'s code will be like a house of cards if the logic is slightly out or timing).\n\nIf you can get it working cleanly with no dropouts, no ghost joins during checks, and no hostname drift, go for it by building on the current infra logic. \nBut touch the detection logic in the wrong place and you\'re on your own if it breaks. (Maybe it is best not switching off Eth because then you\'ll be plugging in a monitor, keyboard, and typing into bash without AI assistance)',NULL,'extendedTextMessage',1776807314,'2026-04-21 21:35:14',NULL,NULL,NULL),
