(4681,'3EB0E2DF78BD4E063DA216','231335629164614@lid',NULL,'Curtis','61466848838:16@s.whatsapp.net','Me',1,'POSForge summary\n\nCurtis feels that POSForge is currently in limbo, with progress happening mainly around payment integrations rather than launch/readiness work like onboarding and market rollout.\nThe biggest blocker is terminal/payment integration support. Resellers are struggling to sell because customers may need to replace EFTPOS hardware, which is stopping deals.\nThe current priority is to make sure Australia and New Zealand have strong EFTPOS coverage first, so resellers can sell confidently.\n\n*Integration status*\n\nLinkly: one integration path is finished, but it was routed down the wrong cloud-native path, so more work is needed to support the broader terminal landscape.\nIngenico: Curtis is chasing this, likely through an APAC/global contact, which could unlock broad coverage.\nWindcave: started, but still in progress.\nTyro: not prioritised earlier, but may be worth revisiting.\nOPay: Curtis agreed to start outreach so that work can begin for Africa as well.\nFiji remains a major market/integration focus, and there was a sense that broader marketing may wait until Fiji is properly supported.\n\n*Product direction*\n\nThe onboarding experience for POSForge hasn’t launched yet and is effectively on hold.\nThere’s active thinking about making onboarding much more differentiated by adding an AI assistant into POSForge, both to guide setup and to act almost like a sales/demo experience.\nThere’s also continued feature work happening in gaps between integrations, such as inventory management and capabilities for businesses like bakeries.\n\n*Sales and go-to-market*\n\nThere was concern that sales and revenue are not moving fast enough, especially given how quickly the AI market is shifting.\nDwayne’s view was that integrations are a real bottleneck, but also that the team needs to better understand why leads aren’t closing—whether the issue is only integrations, or also reseller sales process/training.\nThey agreed there are two major inhibitors:\n1. No polished onboarding for direct customer conversion\nResellers being blocked by unsupported payment terminals\n\n*Operational / stakeholder management*\n\nInvestors and resellers are asking for updates, and Curtis is feeling pressure there.\nA future dashboard/project management layer is being built that could later show investors/resellers:\nprogress on integrations\nfeature roadmap\nsubscription/onboarding data\neventually automated revenue split reporting\n\n*Agreed actions*\n\nCurtis to keep pushing Ingenico\nCurtis to start outreach with OPay\nCurtis to line up Tyro API integration\nDwayne to continue with Windcave and broader integration sequencing\nLonger term: build the dashboard and improved onboarding once the core integration bottlenecks are reduced\n\n*Bottom line:*\nPOSForge’s main issue is not lack of vision or features — it’s that payment terminal compatibility is blocking reseller sales, so integrations are the immediate path to revenue.',NULL,'extendedTextMessage',1779235274,'2026-05-20 00:01:14',NULL,NULL,NULL),
