(4717,'3EB0E0C0993AD1EF2DA736','120363400908812783@g.us',NULL,'Curtis','61466848838:16@s.whatsapp.net','Me',1,'AI summery for you: Overall it was a positive conversation and they were much more comfortable by the end of it than they were at the start. A lot of that came down to the detail around how the platform handles data. I walked them through the fact that the platform stores the assessment and talent data itself, but against pseudonymous identifiers rather than employee names or identities, and that no employee names, contact details or other PII sit in the DataForge platform. I also explained that identity resolution happens back within our Workday environment via API, which gave them a lot more comfort from a privacy and breach-risk perspective.\n\nIt also helped to clarify that this is not a permanently open live integration into Workday. The discussion landed better once I explained that it is more of a controlled pull/push arrangement for current org structure and performance-related data as needed, rather than an always-on connection. I also shared the other points you gave me, including the single-tenant AWS Sydney setup, no subprocessors other than AWS, and the fact that no production data is being used during the MVP build period.\n\nCyber’s position helped as well. I let them know cyber has already reviewed it, is comfortable for it to proceed, and has the risk sitting at medium provided the agreed caveats are met, including the security and access control requirements such as Okta. That seemed to materially reduce their concern.\n\nBy the end of the call Dorothy said the risk looked a lot lower than they had initially expected. The remaining points now seem to be less about the platform itself and more about insurance wording, limits and the short runoff period in the clause. We also talked through the practical side that pushing the insurance cover materially higher would add roughly another $40k, which is obviously significant against the overall package cost.\n\nAnother point that seemed to help was that, while the platform is important, they do not view it as business-critical in the sense of creating major operational failure if it went down. That also lowered the perceived risk profile.\n\nTheir aim was to circle back with a final position tomorrow, so at this stage it feels like we are getting pretty close to sign-off.\n\nThanks again for the detail you sent through beforehand, it was very helpful in the discussion.',NULL,'conversation',1779240906,'2026-05-20 01:35:06',NULL,NULL,NULL),
