(4858,'3EB02CF56DBDFDB037DE45','120363346032343642@g.us',NULL,'Dwayne Baird','144221143048242@lid','Dwayne Baird',0,'Docker packs your software and everything it needs into a container that has all the infrastructure it needs so that it runs the same anywhere.\nTake the Forgebox apps for example they are each individual apps that run independently of one another, Docker goes one further and gives each their own infrastructure, database, web hosting service.\n\nWhat it does in essence, is  if one of your apps crashes, it doesn\'t crash all the others, they all keep running.\n\nDocker is great while everything fits on one machine or one Forgebox. You reach for Kubernetes the moment you outgrow that and need many machines acting as one, staying up no matter what fails.\n\nKubernetes is the manager that runs loads of Docker containers across a bunch of servers at once, automatically starting them, restarting them when they crash, and scaling them up or down if your traffic increases or decreases (cloud cost management) so you don\'t have to babysit them by hand.',NULL,'conversation',1779315684,'2026-05-20 22:21:24',NULL,NULL,NULL),
(4859,'3A8BC365DE72FEA20D5C','120363346032343642@g.us',NULL,'Regan','231335629164614@lid','Regan',0,'https://www.facebook.com/share/r/1C7p339pb9/?mibextid=wwXIfr',NULL,'extendedTextMessage',1779315815,'2026-05-20 22:23:35',NULL,NULL,NULL),
